D. Share insights for Q2.c. [2 Marks]

The pie chart gives the following insights:
The piechart for Churn gives the percentage of Customers who left within the last month. Only 26% of customers has left and 74% of them are still having the connection
Services that each customer has signed up for:
phone - 90% of customers use phone service and 9% use only for Internet
multiple lines- Out of 90% customers who use phone service, 42% customers have multiple lines with or without internet service and 48% have one phone line only
internet - Out of the people who use phone service 22% do not use internet service and 34% use DSL service and 44% use Fiberoptic service.Totally 78% of people use internet service
online security - Out of 78% of Internet service using customers 28% opted for Online security and 50% did not opt for it
online backup - Out of 78% of Internet service using customers 34% opted for Online backup and 44% did not opt for it
device protection - Out of customers using service in all forms 34% opted for device protection and 44% did not opt for it
tech support - Out of customers using service in all forms 29% opted for tech support and 49% did not opt for it
streaming TV and movies - Out of 78% of Internet service using customers 39% opted for streaming TV and movies and 39% did not opt for it

from sklearn import preprocessing
le = preprocessing.LabelEncoder()
entel = pd.DataFrame()
object_col = Tel.columns[pd.Series(Tel.columns).apply(lambda x : Tel[x].dtype == 'O')] 
for i in Tel.columns:
    if i in object_col:
        entel[i] = le.fit_transform(Tel[i])
    else:
        entel[i] = Tel[i]

In [131]:
from sklearn import metrics
from math import sqrt
from sklearn.model_selection import cross_validate
import time

from xgboost import XGBRegressor

def fit_n_print(model, X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test):  # take the model, train data and test data as input
    
    start = time.time()  # note the start time 

    model.fit(X_train, y_train)   # fit the model using the train data

    pred = model.predict(X_test)     # model predictions on the test data

    r2 = metrics.r2_score(y_test, pred)  # calculate the r squared value on the test data
    
    rmse = sqrt(metrics.mean_squared_error(y_test, pred))   # Root mean squared error
     
    scorer = {'r2' : metrics.make_scorer(metrics.r2_score),
              'mse' : metrics.make_scorer(metrics.mean_squared_error),
                             }    # make scorers to be used in cross validation
    
    cv = cross_validate(model, X_train, y_train, cv=10, scoring = scorer)   # perform cross validation accross 3 metrics
    
    r2_cv = cv['test_r2'].mean()                                     # mean r squared value
    rmse_cv = np.mean([sqrt(mse) for mse in cv['test_mse']]) # mean RMSE value(take root of individual mse value and then mean)
    
    
    end = time.time()  #note the end time
    
    
    duration = end - start  # calculate the total duration
    
    
    return r2, rmse,  r2_cv, rmse_cv, duration, pred  # return all the metrics along with predictions

B. Improve performance of the XGBoost as much as possible. Also print best performing parameters along with train and test performance. [5 Marks]

Tuning the number of boosting rounds-Automated boosting round selection using early_stopping

In [68]:
Tel_dmatrix = xg.DMatrix(data=X, label=y)

# Create the parameter dictionary for each tree: params
params = {"objective":"reg:squarederror", "max_depth":4}

# Perform cross-validation with early-stopping: cv_results
cv_results = xg.cv(dtrain=Tel_dmatrix, nfold=3, params=params, metrics="rmse", 
                    early_stopping_rounds=10, num_boost_round=20, as_pandas=True, seed=123)

# Print cv_results
print(cv_results)

XGBoost's hyperparameters:
Common tree tunable parameters
learning rate: learning rate/eta
gamma: min loss reduction to create new tree split
lambda: L2 regularization on leaf weights
alpha: L1 regularization on leaf weights
max_depth: max depth per tree
subsample: % samples used per tree
colsample_bytree: % features used per tree

Tuning learning rate - eta

In [70]:
eta_vals = [0.001, 0.01, 0.1,0.6]
best_rmse = []

# Systematicallyvary the eta
for curr_val in eta_vals:
    params['eta'] = curr_val
    
    # Perform cross-validation: cv_results
    cv_results = xg.cv(dtrain=Tel_dmatrix, params=params, nfold=3,
                        early_stopping_rounds=10, num_boost_round=20, metrics='rmse', seed=123, 
                       as_pandas=True)
    
    # Append the final round rmse to best_rmse
    best_rmse.append(cv_results['test-rmse-mean'].tail().values[-1])
    
# Print the result DataFrame
print(pd.DataFrame(list(zip(eta_vals, best_rmse)), columns=['eta', 'best_rmse']))

Tuning using Grid search with XGBoost

In [73]:
from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV

# Create the parameter grid: gbm_param_grid
gbm_param_grid = {
    'colsample_bytree': [0.3, 0.7],
    'n_estimators': [50,100],
    'max_depth': [2, 5],
    }

# Instantiate the regressor: gbm
gbm = xg.XGBRegressor()

# Perform grid search: grid_mse
grid_mse = GridSearchCV(param_grid=gbm_param_grid, estimator=gbm, 
                        scoring='neg_mean_squared_error', cv=4, verbose=1)

# Fit grid_mse to the data
grid_mse.fit(X, y)

# Print the best parameters and lowest RMSE
print("Best parameters found: ", grid_mse.best_params_)
print("Lowest RMSE found: ", np.sqrt(np.abs(grid_mse.best_score_)))

Fit data using various ensemble techniques

In [95]:
def fit_n_print(model, X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test):  # take the model, train data and test data as input
 global start,pred,r2, rmse, r2_cv, rmse_cv, duration, pred, scorer,cv, r2_cv,end, duration 
 start = time.time()  # note the start time 

 model.fit(X_train, y_train)   # fit the model using the train data

 pred = model.predict(X_test)     # model predictions on the test data

 r2 = metrics.r2_score(y_test, pred)  # calculate the r squared value on the test data
    
 rmse = sqrt(metrics.mean_squared_error(y_test, pred))   # Root mean squared error
    
 #rmsle = sqrt(metrics.mean_squared_log_error(y_test1, pred))  # Root mean squared log error (since the numbers are huge)
    
 scorer = {'r2' : metrics.make_scorer(metrics.r2_score),
              'mse' : metrics.make_scorer(metrics.mean_squared_error),
              #'msle' : metrics.make_scorer(metrics.mean_squared_log_error),
               }    # make scorers to be used in cross validation
    
 cv = cross_validate(model, X_train, y_train, cv=10, scoring = scorer)   # perform cross validation accross 3 metrics
    
 r2_cv = cv['test_r2'].mean()                                     # mean r squared value
 rmse_cv = np.mean([sqrt(mse) for mse in cv['test_mse']]) # mean RMSE value(take root of individual mse value and then mean)
 #rmsle_cv = np.mean([sqrt(msle) for msle in cv['test_msle']]) # mean RMSLE
    
 end = time.time()  #note the end time
    
    
 duration = end - start  # calculate the total duration
    
    
 return r2, rmse, r2_cv, rmse_cv, duration, pred  # return all the metrics along with predictions

def fit_metrics():
 global result1,model
 from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression
 from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeRegressor
 from sklearn.ensemble import BaggingRegressor
 from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestRegressor
 from sklearn.ensemble import GradientBoostingRegressor
 from xgboost import XGBRegressor
 from catboost import CatBoostRegressor
 from lightgbm import LGBMRegressor

 # methods and classes for evaluation
 from sklearn import metrics
 from math import sqrt
 from sklearn.model_selection import cross_validate
 import time
 lr = LinearRegression()        
 dt = DecisionTreeRegressor(random_state=1)   
 br = BaggingRegressor(random_state=1)
 rf = RandomForestRegressor(random_state=1, n_estimators=100)  # specifying n_estimators to avoid "future warnings"
 gb = GradientBoostingRegressor(random_state=1, n_estimators=100)


 result = {}   # Create an empty dictionary to later use to store metrics of each of the models

# putting all 5 models in a for loop and appending the results of each of the models to the 'result' dictionary
 for model, name  in zip([lr, dt, br, rf, gb], ['Linear Regression', 'Decision Tree',
                                                    'Bagging Ensemble', 'Random Forest', 'Gradient Boost Ensemble']):
    result[name] = fit_n_print(model,X_train, X_test,y_train, y_test)
 result1 = pd.DataFrame(np.array(list(result.values()))[:,:-1],    # make a dataframe out of the metrics from result dictionary 
                       columns= ['R Squared', 'MSE', 'R2 CV', 'RMSE CV', 'Elapsed'],
                      index= result.keys())   # use the model names as index

 result1.index.name = 'Model'   # name the index of the result1 dataframe as 'Model'

 print(result1)
